id: volnix-app-public-llm-router
title: Expose VolnixApp.llm_router as a public property
scope: feature
owners: [@TODO]
paths:
  - volnix/app.py
  - tests/integration/test_app_llm_router_property.py
surfaces:
  - VolnixApp.llm_router (new public @property)
dependencies: [workflow]

intent:
  ``VolnixApp`` constructs an ``LLMRouter`` during ``start()`` and
  stashes it at ``self._llm_router``. Library consumers that want
  to construct a higher-level LLM-backed component (Rehearse's
  ``VolnixLiveProvider`` for cassette recording, custom
  bridge providers, observability shims) currently have to reach
  into the underscore-prefixed private attribute, which makes
  their code break on every minor release.

  This TNL exposes ``llm_router`` as a public ``@property`` that
  returns the same instance the engine uses internally. It is the
  exact same pattern as ``session_manager`` (Rehearse gap 1):
  pre-start access returns ``None`` (router is constructed during
  ``start()``); post-start access returns the live ``LLMRouter``.
  No new construction logic; pure accessor exposure.

behaviors:
  - ``VolnixApp`` MUST expose ``llm_router`` as a ``@property``.
    The class-level descriptor MUST be ``isinstance(..., property)``
    so consumers can detect it as a public surface.
  - The property MUST return the same instance internal callers
    see at ``self._llm_router`` (identity check, not a copy or
    proxy). After ``start()``, ``app.llm_router is app._llm_router``
    MUST hold.
  - Pre-start access MUST NOT raise. Returns ``None`` because
    ``_llm_router`` starts at ``None`` and is only wired during
    ``_initialize_llm()`` (step 4 of ``start()``). Matches the
    ``session_manager`` / ``bus`` / ``ledger`` / ``run_manager``
    convention — every public engine accessor on ``VolnixApp``
    is unguarded and optimistically typed, with the contract
    that callers await ``start()`` before depending on the
    instance.
  - The new property MUST be additive — ``self._llm_router``
    remains accessible to internal callers (no rename, no
    deletion). Existing reads like
    ``runtime._llm_router = self._llm_router`` (app.py:1119) MUST
    continue to work unchanged.
  - The property's return-type annotation MUST be the concrete
    ``LLMRouter`` class (mirroring ``session_manager: SessionManager``,
    not ``Any``). Consumer type-checking is the whole point of
    exposing it.
  - Test coverage in ``tests/integration/test_app_llm_router_property.py``
    MUST mirror ``test_app_session_manager_property.py``'s four
    tests:
    - ``test_positive_property_exists_on_class`` (descriptor check)
    - ``test_negative_property_returns_none_before_start``
    - ``test_positive_property_returns_router_after_start`` (also
      asserts ``isinstance(app.llm_router, LLMRouter)`` and
      ``app.llm_router is app._llm_router``)
    - ``test_positive_underscore_attribute_remains_accessible``

non-goals:
  - No new construction logic. The router is already built by
    ``_initialize_llm()``; this TNL is pure accessor exposure.
  - No changes to ``LLMRouter`` itself.
  - No changes to ``register_provider`` (that public wrapper
    already exists from PMF 4C Step 8).
  - No deprecation of ``self._llm_router`` — internal callers
    keep using it; the property is purely additive.

rationale:
  Identical pattern to Rehearse gap 1 (``session_manager``). The
  router is the public seam through which every LLM call flows;
  exposing it as a property lets downstream products construct
  router-backed components without import-path-violating reaches
  into private state.
